    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i have a physics exam coming up and i'm struggling a bit with the concept of quantum entanglement. can you give me a concise, non-mathematical summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre connection between two or more particles, where their fates become linked no matter how far apart they are. Measuring a property of one entangled particle instantaneously tells you the corresponding property of the other, even if it's across the galaxy. This is fundamentally different from classical correlation, like having two gloves in separate boxes; knowing one is left-handed doesn't *force* the other to be right-handed until you look, but in entanglement, the properties aren't set until the moment of measurement. It's a shared, instantaneous quantum state.",
      "source": "target",
