    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense but it still sounds a bit weird. i keep reading about how einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seems to defy how things should work. why exactly did he call it \"spooky\"? what's the part that's actually so unsettling about it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein found it \"spooky\" because it seemed to violate the principle of locality, which is the idea that an object can only be influenced by its immediate surroundings. The unsettling part is that the correlation happens *instantaneously*, which seems to imply information is traveling faster than the speed of light. He felt this \"spooky action\" suggested that quantum mechanics was incomplete, as it seemed to allow for non-local influences without any apparent physical mechanism to explain them. It challenges our everyday intuition about how cause and effect should operate in space.",
      "source": "target",
